AdG became the second most popular in Germany
The anti-immigrant " Alternative for Germany " beats another record of popularity , and Angela Merkel 's ratings are falling .
Apparently , the people of Germany have begun to be seriously tired of Angela Merkel ’ s immigration policy , which has made the country the desired target for millions of refugees from the Middle East .
This is most evident in recent social surveys , according to which the anti-immigrant party Alternative for Germany is becoming more popular , and the positions of the ruling bloc Merkel and Seehofer are weakening .
This week , the AdG hit another record , rising to the second line in the rating of popular sympathies .
Right-wing conservatives , with 17 percent of popularity , managed to bypass the Social Democrats , who have about 16 percent .
The gap of one percentage point could be written off for statistical error , but the fact that the ADG , created in 2013 from a small group of Euroskeptics economists , had managed to become a serious political force .
The leadership in the overall ranking continues to hold the ruling CSU / CDU bloc , which has about 30 percent .
However , there is a tendency to lose points - as early as April , support for Angela Merkel ’ s bloc was four percentage points higher .
The personal rating of the German Chancellor , who heads the German government for the fourth consecutive term , is also decreasing .
Today , 48 percent of Germans support Angela Merkel , 7 percent lower than last year .
Let us add that the Social Democrats were followed by the " green " ( 15 % ) , the left ( 11 % ) and the liberals ( 10 % ) .
Evolution of " Alternatives "
The Alternative for Germany Party was established in September 2012 on the basis of the Alternative Choice 2013 group , which included people from the Christian Democratic Union .
The group initially opposed the government policy , but initially dealt only with economic issues , including the euro and EU cooperation .
At the same time , the group opposed the " sponsorship " by Germany of weak EU economies , did not rule out the possibility of a return to the German mark and a complete withdrawal of the country from the EU .
Against the background of the deepening immigration crisis , the political platform of the ADG has expanded .
In 2013 , the group became a full-fledged party , which took the niche of Euroskeptics and began to harshly criticize the government for the failure of immigration policy .
In the last parliamentary elections in 2017 , the APG managed to break through the Bundestag for the first time , having received 94 seats ( out of 709 ) .
Two representatives of " Alternatives for Germany " get seats in the European Parliament .
