Named the death date of the universe
The universe will last for about 140 billion years , ten times the age of the observed world , about 13.8 billion years .
The study of the international team of scientists is published in the library of electronic preprints arXiv.org and is aimed at publishing in the journal Publications of the Astronomical Society of Japan , the Japanese newspaper Asahi Shimbun reports .
The experts came to such conclusions by watching with the help of the Hyper Suprime-Cam camera of Subaru telescope for about ten million galaxies .
After tracking the distribution of dark matter and dark energy , which account for more than 95 per cent of the energy mass of the observed world , scientists , working under the standard cosmological model <unk> CDM ( <unk> Cold Dark Matter ) , estimated the pace of expansion of the universe , which was slightly slower than previously thought .
A press release from the Subaru Observatory noted that the observations had produced a detailed three-dimensional map of the distribution of matter in the universe , and the inclusion of data from the European space telescope Planck had clarified the limitations imposed on the LCDM parameters .
In July , scientists modeled the possible death of the universe .
Three years earlier , their colleagues presented new arguments that the observed world would cease to exist in 22 billion years as a result of the Great Gap .
